, and incomplete, political, economic, and security transition. In Afghanistan: Transition under Threat, leading Afghanistan scholars and practitioners paint a full picture of the situation in Afghanistan and the impact of international and particularly Canadian assistance. They review the achievements of the reconstruction process and outline future challenges, focusing on key issues like the narcotics trade, the Pakistan—Afghanistan bilateral relationship, the Taliban-led insurgency, and continuing endemic poverty. This collection provides new insight into the nature and state of Afghanistan’s post-conflict transition and illustrates the consequences of failure. Co-published with the Centre for International Governance Innovation  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aHistory: Military History. 4aPolitical Science. 4aPolitical Science: International Relations. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh1 aBanerjee, Nipa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aByrd, William A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapstick, M.D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiustozzi, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodhand, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaqqani, Husain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Geoffrey, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJalali, Ali A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaley, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatel, Seema, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct